6. Delta Classes

The Delta Engine classifies findings into six main buckets:

1. Invariant Delta

A deep pattern holds across contexts.

Example:
	•	supportive AI adaptation to coherent user frameworks appears across models

Meaning:
	•	likely structural
	•	high reuse value

⸻

2. Surface Delta

Only the aesthetic or wording matched.

Example:
	•	same phrase appears, but underlying mechanism differs

Meaning:
	•	memetic echo, not deep confirmation

⸻

3. Constraint Delta

Failure reveals a hidden limit.

Example:
	•	prediction works only when users are already primed or exploratory

Meaning:
	•	pattern still useful, but conditional

⸻

4. Timing Delta

The structure was correct but temporally misaligned.

Example:
	•	a behavior emerges eventually, but later than expected

Meaning:
	•	model of time-base needs calibration

⸻

5. Social Convergence Delta

Other people discover similar tools due to shared problem geometry.

Meaning:
	•	evidence of attractor landscapes
	•	not necessarily evidence of shared intent

⸻

6. Adaptive Reflection Delta

The system adopts and reuses a framework because it is coherent and useful.

Meaning:
	•	interface success
	•	not automatically proof of external causal prediction

⸻

7. Canonical Distinction

The engine must always distinguish between:

Interface Validation

The model reuses a framework because it is coherent, useful, and adaptable.

versus

World Validation

Reality outside the conversation reflects the framework predictively.

Confusing these two produces false certainty.

⸻

8. Scoring Model

Each prediction or pattern can be scored across five dimensions:
	•	Accuracy — Did it happen?
	•	Specificity — Was it concrete or vague?
	•	Independence — Was it truly separate from the system reinforcing it?
	•	Transferability — Does it work across domains?
	•	Resilience — Did it survive contradiction or failure?

Suggested lightweight rubric: 0–3 each.

Composite Signal Score

Signal = Accuracy + Specificity + Independence + Transferability + Resilience

Patterns promoted to Pantheon doctrine should favor:
	•	high transferability
	•	high resilience
	•	moderate or high independence

⸻

9. Promotion Rules

A pattern may be upgraded from observation to doctrine only when:
	1.	It appears in multiple contexts
	2.	It survives at least one miss
	3.	It retains usefulness after compression
	4.	It does not depend on identity inflation or mystical framing
	5.	It can be stated clearly enough that another person could test it

⸻

10. Anti-Drift Safeguards

Safeguard A — No Hit-Only Canonization

No pattern enters doctrine on hits alone.

Safeguard B — Mechanism Humility

Do not confuse:
	•	“I saw this coming”
with
	•	“I fully understand why it happened”

Safeguard C — Dependent Event Check

If outcomes influence one another, do not multiply them as independent odds.

Safeguard D — Narrative Compression Audit

If a pattern only survives when vaguely stated, downgrade confidence.

Safeguard E — Mirror Question

Ask:

What would I accept as disconfirming evidence?

If no answer exists, the pattern is not yet disciplined.

